[Patient] How much fluid should I drink daily to manage my heart failure?
[Healthcare Educator] Aim for around 1.5-2 liters of fluid per day, including water, soups, and juices.
[Patient] Should I limit my salt intake as well?
[Healthcare Educator] Yes, reducing salt can help manage fluid retention and heart failure symptoms. 
[Patient] Can I drink coffee or tea as part of my fluid intake?
[Healthcare Educator] Limit caffeine intake as it can affect fluid balance. Opt for decaffeinated options instead.
[Patient] How can I tell if I am retaining too much fluid?
[Healthcare Educator] Watch for swelling in your legs, sudden weight gain, or difficulty breathing. These are signs.
[Patient] What should I do if I notice these symptoms?
[Healthcare Educator] Contact your healthcare provider immediately if you experience these symptoms for further evaluation.
[Patient] Are there any foods that can help with fluid management?
[Healthcare Educator] Foods like watermelon, cucumbers, and leafy greens can help with hydration and fluid balance.
[Patient] Can I have a glass of wine or beer occasionally?
[Healthcare Educator] Limit alcohol intake as it can worsen heart failure symptoms and interact with medications.
[Patient] How often should I weigh myself to monitor fluid retention?
[Healthcare Educator] Weigh yourself at the same time each day and report any sudden weight changes to your provider.
[Patient] Is it okay to drink sports drinks for hydration?
[Healthcare Educator] Sports drinks can be high in sugar and sodium, so opt for water or low-sugar options.
[Patient] Should I be concerned about drinking too much water?
[Healthcare Educator] Drinking excessive water can also be harmful, so aim for a balanced intake throughout the day.
[Patient] Can I take diuretics to help with fluid management?
[Healthcare Educator] Diuretics can be prescribed by your healthcare provider to help with fluid retention in some cases.
[Patient] How can I stay motivated to stick to these fluid intake recommendations?
[Healthcare Educator] Keeping a log of your daily fluid intake and setting reminders can help you stay on track.